Data Source¶

The data is from one of my Python classes last semester. My professor Brian C. Keegan wrote the function that fetches the page view and the revision data of an article from the Wikipedia. I chose the 'Coronavirus disease 2019' Wikipedia article and did all the data cleaning work and exported the data to a new CSV file to do the visualization for this assignment.

Motivation and Research Question¶

I chose 'Coronavirus disease 2019' Wikipedia article to analyze. Covid-19 pandemic is known to have erupted in China at the end of 2019. According to statistics from The New York Times, there were 88 new cases in the United States on March 1st, and the number of new cases continued to rise over time. On June 16th, the daily number of new cases even reached 75000.

The number of page revisions may show when people began to pay attention to the Covid-19. Because more editions mean more awareness and updates about the virus. We can probably see whether people in the world(at least for people who speak English) began to learn the Covid-19 when the pandemic broke out in China, or they started to learn it when the Covid-19 appeared and broke out all over the world.

Therefore, my research question is: by looking at the Wikipedia revision data, when did people start to pay attention to the Covid-19 and whether it is related to the number of new cases?

Visualization¶

Scatter plot¶

Firstly, because the Altair can't load more than 5000 record of data, so I need to drop some rows from my original csv file.

I created a new column called 'month' for the visualization. Also, the column "lag" means the time elapsed since the previous edit, and the unit is in hours. The column "diff" is the change in the web page "size" since the last revision. I will make a scatter plot of these two columns.

Interpretation and Disccusion¶

From the chart, we can see that most of the revision sizes are small between -200 and 600. The time interval between these revision records is very short as well, and the most frequent revision activity is within 0 to 3 hours. Although thhe scatter chart seems to be symmetrical, we can find that more dots in the positive direction of the y-axis, which means the revision of adding contents is more. Also, from the dots colors, we can kind of have a sense that there're many yellow, green, and purple dots. That means after April, there are more revisions than before.

However, because these points are overlaping each other in the scatter plot, it's hard to see which month has the most changes. So in the next visualization, let's make a line graph with the time line to explore the trend of the revisions.

Line Plot¶

I used pandas's groupby function to count the number of revisions by day and created a line plot

In [100]:
daily_gb = revision_data.groupby(pd.Grouper(key='timestamp',freq='1D'))

daily_rev_counts = daily_gb.agg({'sha1':'count'})

#rename column
daily_rev_counts = daily_rev_counts.rename(columns={'sha1': 'counts'})

Interpretation¶

We can see that there's a considerable increase in the revision times is in mid-March, even more than 200 reevision records at its peak. If we compare the number of new cases globally, we can find that the global new cases statistics can correspond to this revision chart. So there is some relation between the outbreak in March around the world and the revision activity.

Besides, if we look at the statistics of the number of new cases in the United States, this number reached two peaks at the beginning of April and the middle of June, which also correspond with the revision counts.

Interpretation¶

Firstly, the timezone that Wikipedia used for the revision history is UTC time by default at the English Wikipedia. The heatmap shows that most revisions are made at 10pm on Wednesday and 5am on Thursday. However, because the time of this revision history is UTC, and there's no coordinate local time of each revsion, it's hard to see when people usually edit an article during a day. But I made another pivot table called rev_wed_df, trying to see whether there is any big news in the past Wednesdays that caused such revisions. According to the new cases world statistics, the number of new cases in the whole world exceeded 1w for the first time on the 13th. On March 12th, only 6000 cases were confirmed, but 11107 were confirmed positive on the 13th. So I guess that's why there was this amount of revision on that day.

Conclusion and Discussion¶

My research question is “when did most of people begin to pay attention to the Covid-19 epidemic and whether it is related to the new cases?” So the answer is that people started to search Covid-19 on Wikipedia from March to April, and yes, I think it has a direct relationship with the number of new cases.

As I mentioned earlier, the first outbreak of the Covid-19 pandemic in the world was in Wuhan China in 2019, and then it started to break out all over the world in March 2020. As can be saw from the revisions line chart, before March, there were not many people editing the page, and those volunteer writers started an active revision activity around April.

I think it has a direct relationship with the number of new cases because more new cases mean a greater impact on society. More new cases mean that people's understanding of the Covid-19 is updated faster, resulting in an increase or decrease in the number of revisions.
